05664nam a22007455i 9781684480418DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97816844804187 a10.36019/97816844804182doi  a(DE-B1597)541222  a(OCoLC)1100878240  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aPN56.R33bW54 2019eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a809/.933522231 aWiggins, Ellwood, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aOdysseys of Recognition :bPerforming Intersubjectivity in Homer, Aristotle, Shakespeare, Goethe, and Kleist /cEllwood Wiggins. 1aLewisburg, PA : bBucknell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©2019  a1 online resource (298 p.) :b2 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Studies in the Age of Goethe00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tOverview of Contents -- tAbbreviations -- tA Note on Translations and Orthography -- tIntroduction: Performing Recognition -- tPart I. Marking the Limits of Recognition: Between Aristotle and the Odyssey -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER ONE. "Just as the Name Itself Signifies": Under the Sign of Nostalgia -- tCHAPTER TWO. "Recognition Is a Change": Performance in Motion -- tCHAPTER THREE. "From Ignorance to Knowledge": Penelope's Poetological Epistemology -- tCHAPTER FOUR. "Into Friendship or Enmity": An Ethics of Authentic Deception -- tCHAPTER FIVE. "For Those Bound for Good or Bad Fortune": Casualties of Recognition -- tPart II. Outing Interiority: Modern Recognitions -- tIntroduction -- tCHAPTER SIX. Self-Knowledge between Plato and Shakespeare: Alcibiades I and Troilus and Cressida -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Metamorphoses of Recognition: Goethe's "Fortunate Event" -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Epistemologies of Recognition: Goethe's Iphigenie auf Tauris and the Spectacle of Catharsis -- tCHAPTER NINE. Politics of Recognition: Friends, Enemies, and Goethe's Iphigenie -- tCHAPTER TEN. The Fate of Recognition: Kleist's Penthesilea -- tConcluding Reflections: Signifying Silence in Blumenberg and Kafka -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aLiterary recognition is a technical term for a climactic plot device. Odysseys of Recognition claims that interpersonal recognition is constituted by performance, and brings performance theory into dialogue with poetics, politics, and philosophy. By observing Odysseus figures from Homer to Kleist, Ellwood Wiggins offers an alternative to conventional intellectual histories that situate the invention of the interior self in modernity. Through strategic readings of Aristotle, this elegantly written, innovative study recovers an understanding of interpersonal recognition that has become strange and counterintuitive. Penelope in Homer's Odyssey offers a model for agency in ethical knowledge that has a lot to teach us today. Early modern and eighteenth-century characters, meanwhile, discover themselves not deep within an impenetrable self, but in the interpersonal space between people in the world. Recognition, Wiggins contends, is the moment in which epistemology and ethics coincide: in which what we know becomes manifest in what we do. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aIntersubjectivity in literature. 0aRecognition in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Literary, Cultural and Area Stud. 20